{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611529"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:11:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:11:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16224"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16224","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16224"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.39,0.04,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8915"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64405"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8915","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8915"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16224"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49837"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"247"},{"type":"tags","id":"2044"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8179"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21213"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21216"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64405"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA woman presents for breast imaging. Mammogram shows an area of architectural distortion with a stellate appearance. The lesion demonstrates cystic changes and epithelial proliferation in a radiating pattern. The appearance mimics tubular carcinoma but is confirmed to be benign.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ductal hyperplasia","Fibrocystic change","Radial scar","Fat necrosis","Mammary duct ectasia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe description is classic for a \u003Cstrong\u003Eradial scar\u003C/strong\u003E, which is a benign breast lesion characterized by a central fibroelastic core with radiating ducts and tubules. These lesions typically show architectural distortion on mammography and can mimic carcinoma, particularly tubular carcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options can be excluded:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuctal hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E typically does not cause architectural distortion or have a stellate appearance on imaging\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrocystic change\u003C/strong\u003E may show cysts but lacks the characteristic stellate appearance\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFat necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E can appear as an irregular mass but typically has associated calcifications and occurs after trauma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMammary duct ectasia\u003C/strong\u003E shows dilated ducts but does not have a radiating pattern or architectural distortion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile radial scars are benign, they are considered a risk factor for subsequent breast cancer development and may require excision for definitive diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A radial scar is a benign breast lesion that can mimic carcinoma on imaging due to its stellate appearance and architectural distortion.","Key histological features of radial scars include a central fibroelastic core with radiating ducts and tubules, along with varying degrees of epithelial proliferation."],"references":["Kennedy M, Masterson AV, Kerin M, Flanagan F. Pathology and clinical relevance of radial scars: a review. J Clin Pathol. 2003 Oct;56(10):721-4. doi: 10.1136/jcp.56.10.721. PMID: 14514771; PMCID: PMC1770086.","Furukawa M, Taira N, Iha S, Nogami T, Shien T, Omori M, Doihara H. A radial sclerosing lesion mimicking breast cancer on mammography in a young woman. Case Rep Oncol. 2012 Jan;5(1):99-103. doi: 10.1159/000337024. Epub 2012 Feb 25. PMID: 22539921; PMCID: PMC3337735.","Trombadori CML, D\u0027Angelo A, Ferrara F, Santoro A, Belli P, Manfredi R. Radial Scar: a management dilemma. Radiol Med. 2021 Jun;126(6):774-785. doi: 10.1007/s11547-021-01344-w. Epub 2021 Mar 20. PMID: 33743143; PMCID: PMC8154762.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49837"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16224"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49837"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T14:55:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-23T14:56:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8915"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64405"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"typ